A 13-year-old boy was hospitalized because of acute abdominal pain, melena, and vomiting. Mild abdominal pain was present for the preceding 6 months in the right lower quadrant. No weight loss or other specific symptoms were present. Before the onset of the symptoms, no signs of malignancy were present and he had not undergone a thorough abdominal examination till then. Additionally, he did not have any chronic diseases and had no family history of malignancy. Distended abdomen and decreased bowel sounds were observed during the physical examination. Diffuse direct and indirect tenderness was present throughout the abdomen. At presentation, melena was present; however, blood pressure and other vital signs were normal.
